IS  - 1
KW  - Markov switching
KW  - monetary union
KW  - equilibrium stability and uniqueness
KW  - monetary–fiscal interactions
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-2879
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jmcb.12699
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract Earlier studies on the stability of monetary unions show that an inflation-targeting central bank imposes strict budgetary requirements on fiscal policy to obtain a unique stable equilibrium. Failure of only one fiscal authority to meet these requirements already results in nonexistence of equilibrium. Nevertheless, it might prove useful to temporarily depart from such requirements in order to absorb country-specific shocks. We show that such departures are feasible if fiscal authorities commit to switch to more sustainable fiscal regimes in the future. Debt devaluation and fiscal bailouts may also broaden the range of policy stances under which monetary unions are stable.
ER  - 

